1) What is a non-static method in Java, and how is it different from a static method?
-->
| Feature      | Non-static Method                   | Static Method                   |
| ------------ | ----------------------------------- | ------------------------------- |
| Belongs to   | Object                              | Class                           |
| Invocation   | Object reference                    | Class name                      |
| Access       | Can access both static & non-static | Can access only static directly |
| Polymorphism | Supports overriding                 | No overriding (only hiding)     |



2) When and how can a non-static method be invoked?
-->👉 It can be invoked only after creating an object
    class Demo {
        void show() {
            System.out.println("Non-static method");
        }
    
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            Demo obj = new Demo();
            obj.show(); // ✅ call through object
        }
    }


3) Can a non-static method access static variables and methods? Why or why not?
-->✅ Yes
    
    👉 Because:
    
    Static members belong to the class
    Object (non-static context) has access to class-level members
    class Test {
        static int a = 10;
    
        void display() {
            System.out.println(a); // ✅ allowed
        }
    }



4) Can a static method call a non-static method directly? Explain with reason.
-->❌ No

    👉 Reason:
    
    Static method has no object context
    Non-static methods require an object
    ✅ Correct way:
    class Demo {
        void show() {
            System.out.println("Hello");
        }
    
        static void test() {
            Demo obj = new Demo();
            obj.show(); // ✅ through object
        }
    }


5) How does memory allocation differ for static and non-static methods in the JVM?
-->👉 ALL methods (static + non-static) are stored in the Method Area (class area)

    Only one copy exists
    Shared by all objects
    👉 Both methods’ code is stored in the method area
        
        🔹 Difference:
        Static methods
        Loaded once when class loads
        Shared across all objects

        Non-static methods
        Also stored once in method area
        But executed using object reference (stack uses object context)
        
        👉 Key idea:
        
        Methods are not duplicated per object
        Only data (variables) differ per object


6) Can we use the this keyword inside a non-static method? Why?
-->✅ Yes
    
    👉 Because:
    
    this refers to the current object
    Non-static methods are always called using an object
    class Demo {
        int x = 10;
    
        void show() {
            System.out.println(this.x); // refers to current object
        }
    }


7) When are non-static methods loaded into memory?
-->👉 Non-static methods are loaded when the class is loaded into the JVM, not when objects are created.
    
    Stored in the Method Area
    Only one copy exists, shared by all objects
    ✔ Object creation does not load methods again



8) Can a non-static method be overridden in a subclass? Explain with an example.
-->✅ Yes — this is runtime polymorphism

    Example:
    class Parent {
        void show() {
            System.out.println("Parent method");
        }
    }
    
    class Child extends Parent {
        @Override
        void show() {
            System.out.println("Child method");
        }
    }
    
    public class Test {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            Parent obj = new Child();
            obj.show(); // runtime decision
        }
    }
    🔹 Output:
    Child method
    
    👉 JVM decides at runtime based on actual object (Child)




9) What happens if we try to call a non-static method using a null object reference?
-->❌ It throws NullPointerException   
    class Demo {
        void show() {
            System.out.println("Hello");
        }
    }
    
    public class Test {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            Demo obj = null;
            obj.show(); // ❌ Exception
        }
    }
    👉 Because non-static methods need a valid object




10) Can a non-static method be declared as final, abstract, or synchronized? What are the implications?
-->✅ Yes, all are possible — but with different meanings:
    
    🔹 final method
    final void show() {}
    
    👉 Cannot be overridden in subclass
    
    🔹 abstract method
    abstract void show();
    
    👉 No body → must be implemented by subclass
    👉 Class must be declared abstract
    
    🔹 synchronized method
    synchronized void show() {}
    
    👉 Only one thread can access at a time (object-level lock)
| Modifier     | Allowed? | Meaning            |
| ------------ | -------- | ------------------ |
| final        | ✅        | Prevent overriding |
| abstract     | ✅        | No implementation  |
| synchronized | ✅        | Thread safety      |


